Results Under Various levels of Data Heterogeneity and Datasets.
TableÂ 1 presents the performance results of various methods with different levels of Dirichlet-based label distribution shift (Î²âˆˆ{0.5,0.1,0.05}ğ›½0.50.10.05\beta\in\{0.5,0.1,0.05\}).
Our method consistently achieves notably higher accuracy compared to other state-of-the-art (SOTA) methods across all scenarios.
As the degree of data heterogeneity increases, competing methods struggle to maintain their performance levels.
Specifically, FedLCÂ (Zhang etÂ al., 2022) experiences a substantial decline, dropping even below the performance of the classic method FedAvg when Î²=0.05ğ›½0.05\beta=0.05.
This decline stems from each client having numerous empty classes in extreme cases, a factor overlooked by FedLCÂ (Zhang etÂ al., 2022).
Conversely, our method consistently upholds excellent performance, especially in highly heterogeneous label distribution scenarios.
For instance, in the case of the CIFAR10 dataset with Î²=0.05ğ›½0.05\beta=0.05, our method achieves an impressive test accuracy of 75.71%, surpassing FedAvg by 12.81%.
This outcome highlights the efficacy of our approach in remedying the accuracy decline observed in both empty and minority classes, effectively mitigating instances of local overfitting.
Additionally, we present the performance of these methods for quantity-based label distribution shift in TableÂ 2, further emphasizing the superiority of our method.

Impact of Different Numbers of Communication Round.
In real-world scenarios, limitations frequently arise concerning the communication rounds. To address this, we conducted tests to evaluate performance across various communication round limits on the CIFAR10 dataset, considering Î²=0.1ğ›½0.1\beta=0.1 and Î²=0.05ğ›½0.05\beta=0.05. The results, outlined in TableÂ 4, reveal a notable trend: as the communication rounds decrease, the accuracy of most methods experiences a significant decline. However, our method stands out by maintaining a high level of accuracy even with a reduced number of communication rounds. This highlights the robustness of FedED in scenarios with limited communication rounds.

Effectiveness of Different Objectives.
Our approach comprises two key objectives: empty-classes distillation and logit suppression.
To gauge the effectiveness of each objective, we conducted experiments on CIFAR10 with Î²=0.05ğ›½0.05\beta=0.05, presenting the results in TableÂ 5.
In comparison to FedLCÂ (Zhang etÂ al., 2022), empty-classes distillation and logit suppression both showcase notable performance improvements, which demonstrates the effectiveness of our two key objectives.
Additionally, when combined with the empty-classes distillation, the logit suppression further amplifies the overall model performance.

Combination with Other Techniques.
In this section, we integrated our method with two SOTA methods, FedEXPÂ (Jhunjhunwala etÂ al., 2023) and FedSAMÂ (Qu etÂ al., 2022), detailed in TableÂ 6.
The combination of our method with FedEXPÂ (Jhunjhunwala etÂ al., 2023) and FedSAMÂ (Qu etÂ al., 2022) results in improved performance.
This enhancement is reasonable because FedEXP focuses on optimizing the server update for an improved learning rate, and FedSAM emphasizes local gradient descent to achieve a smoother loss landscape.
These elements complement well with our core idea, which finally results in enhanced performance when combined.
